data.name: label8.Text
data.value: The cerebellar crust consists of three layers of cells that, from the surface to the depth, are: The molecular layer, Purkinje cells and the granular layer. • Surface layer (molecular). It is located under the meninges, being low in cells and high in fiber. Neurones are represented by the star cells, whose axons form a basket-like network around the bodies of Purkinje cells. Through their dendrites, the cells in the basket and the star cells establish synaptic contacts with the axon of the granular cells. • The intermediate layer. It contains the bodies of Purkinje cells, with a piriform appearance, arranged on a single row. Their abundant branched dendritic extensions penetrate the molecular layer, where they will establish synapses with the axons of granular cells. The Axons of Purkinje cells leave the bark of the cerebellum, pass through the white matter and come into contact with the nuclei of the cerebellum. • Deep (granular) layer. It consists of small granular neurones (4 to 8 microns), but very numerous. Their short dendrites remain in the granular layer, and the long axon reaches the superficial layer, where it divides into T, with each branch of T connecting with the dendrites of Purkinje cells and star cells. In the granular layer are also found Golgi II cells, whose dendrites end up in the molecular layer. Their Axon is short and remains in the granular layer, participating in the formation of the cerebellar glomerulus. There are two types of fibers in the brain: • musciform fibers, which end in granular cell dendrites, constituting cerebellar glomeruli (neurofibril). The structure of the neuropathic also includes the short axis of Golgi II cells; • Hanging fibers, which end on the dendrites of Purkinje cells.

data.name: label7.Text
data.value: The cerebellum is derived from all sensory and motor pathways and is therefore informed of all stimuli from the external or internal environment. Through the processes of integrating the received information, it can exert a coordinating action on the muscle activity initiated by the motor cerebral cortex. That explains why cerebellar lesions give coordination disorders.

data.name: label5.Text
data.value: On the outside is a layer of gray matter that forms the bark of the cerebellum. The cerebellar bark surrounds the central white substance, which sends extensions into the foils, giving, overall, the appearance of a tree crown, hence the name of the Tree of life. Inside the mass of white matter are masses of gray matter that form the deep nuclei of the cerebellum. In the vermis are the fastigial nuclei (left and right), and in the cerebellar hemispheres, in the mediolateral sense, are the globous nucleus, the emboliform nucleus and the toothed nucleus. Fastigial nuclei are the oldest phylogenetic (belong to the archicerebellum), while toothed nuclei are the newest phylogenetic (belong to the neocerebellum).

data.name: label3.Text
data.value: The cerebellum is bound to the bulb, bridge and mesenchephalous by the inferior, medium and upper cerebellar peduncles. These peduncles contain afferent and efferent (projection) fibers. The surface of the cerebellum is furrowed by parallel grooves with different depths. Some are numerous and superficial, delineating the cerebellar leaves, others, deeper but rarer, delimit the cerebellum lobules, and finally others, the deepest, such as the primary fissure and posterolateral fissure, delimit the cerebellum lobules. From an ontogenetic and functional location point of view, the cerebellum can be divided into three lobes: The flocculonodular lobe, the anterior lobe, and the posterior lobe. • The flocculonodular lobe comprises the nodus, both flocculus and peduncles of the flocculus. It is separated from the rest of the cerebellum by the posterolateral fissure, the first to appear onto- and phylogenetically. Together with the lingula, it forms the oldest part of the cerebellum (the archerebellum) and represents the center of vestibular balance, the center of orientation and the center of maintaining the position of the head (an essential factor for maintaining balance). Because it has connections to the vestibular analyzer it is also called vestibulocerebel. • The anterior lobe, previously located by the primary fissure, consists of the culmen and central lobe on the vermis, the quadrilateral lobe, and the central lobe wing on the hemispheres. It represents the second part of the cerebellum that appears in phylogeneesis (paleocerebel) next to the pyramid and uvula on the lower face of the vermis. Since the paleocerebellum is linked to the spinal cord, it is also called a spinocerebellum and is the center for controlling the posture tone of the antigravity extensor muscles, which act as compensation and opposition to the forces of gravity. • The posterior lobe is the part of the cerebellum between the primary fissure and the posterolateral fissure. It represents the newest phylogenetic part (neocerebellum), excluding the pyramid and uvula functionally linked to paleocerebel.

data.name: label9.Text
data.value: The cerebellum occupies the posterior fossa of the skull, being separated from the cerebral hemispheres by the cerebellum tent, an addiction of the cerebral pain mater. It is located behind the bulb and the bridge with which it delimits the cavity of the IV ventricle. It has the shape of a butterfly, showing a middle portion (vermis) and two bulky side portions called cerebellar hemispheres. The emisferes have an upper side covered by the cerebellum tent and a lower side in the center of which is a depression called the valecula, which contains the lower part of the vermis.
